<node id="Echinodermata">
  <data key="d0">Echinodermata</data>
  <data key="d1">taxon</data>
  <data key="d2">Echinodermata is a phylum of marine invertebrates. This taxonomic group includes a diverse array of organisms such as starfish, sea urchins, and related species. All described starfish species belong to this phylum, and specific examples within Echinodermata include *Luidia sarsii africana*, *Chondraster elattosis*, *Spoladaster veneris*, and *Poraniopsis echinaster*. 

Echinoderms are characterized by distinctive anatomical features, including a stellate (star-shaped) body, a reticular skeleton, raised spines, tube feet, and a white madreporite. As marine invertebrates, members of this phylum are found in various oceanic environments and are often mentioned in scientific descriptions and imagery contexts. The phylum represents a major group within the animal kingdom, encompassing a wide range of species that share these common morphological traits.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b7d87a9fdd6796fbc3a24c40022179ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5bd15d157743c89b7fd9be20dd1df380&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0f7451703f2287af83a619489c9a745&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-83d371544d6eb48b5321717428ea68f1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6312bf3bcdf9b3397dffc439b6ad9d04&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-492e7a51e0a2392955e5726fd9c64f77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1ff0eb99ae21e17d67fdd1dbba08d515&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-37cbd16434444d9480d8632be65be39c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c2277bdb0cfb9e13e612107b546b5702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-193d40aeb45ee8e91a4034e163403a2b</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097479</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="P. echinaster">
  <data key="d0">P. echinaster</data>
  <data key="d1">species</data>
  <data key="d2">A species of starfish described in the field guide, with short-armed stellate body form, reticular skeleton, raised spines on aboral surface, two rows of tube feet, and white madreporite. Colour ranges from deep orange to red or pure white. Found in the South Atlantic including West Coast of South Africa.&lt;SEP&gt;A species mentioned in the document, with arms clearly defined and having size averaging 50-160 mm diameter.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b7d87a9fdd6796fbc3a24c40022179ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-272e62d6d62e10360c47dab598eb09e1</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097502</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Lophaster quadrispinus">
  <data key="d0">Lophaster quadrispinus</data>
  <data key="d1">species</data>
  <data key="d2">A similar species to P. echinaster, with many dense raised tubercles on the aboral surface.&lt;SEP&gt;A similar species described in the document, having many dense raised tubercles on the aboral surface.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b7d87a9fdd6796fbc3a24c40022179ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-272e62d6d62e10360c47dab598eb09e1</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097502</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Diplopteraster multipes">
  <data key="d0">Diplopteraster multipes</data>
  <data key="d1">species</data>
  <data key="d2">A similar species to P. echinaster, more cushion-like with arms not as clearly defined.&lt;SEP&gt;A similar species described in the document, more cushion-like with arms not as clearly defined as P. echinaster.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b7d87a9fdd6796fbc3a24c40022179ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-272e62d6d62e10360c47dab598eb09e1</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097503</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="South Atlantic West Coast of South Africa">
  <data key="d0">South Atlantic West Coast of South Africa</data>
  <data key="d1">distribution</data>
  <data key="d2">Geographic distribution of P. echinaster, including the South Atlantic Ocean and the west coast of South Africa.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b7d87a9fdd6796fbc3a24c40022179ca</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781095614</data>
