  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Arm Curling">
  <data key="d0">Arm Curling</data>
  <data key="d1">behavior</data>
  <data key="d2">Behavior of P. echinaster where the ends of arms often turn upwards or curl inwards.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b7d87a9fdd6796fbc3a24c40022179ca</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781095618</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Oral Surface">
  <data key="d0">Oral Surface</data>
  <data key="d1">anatomical_feature</data>
  <data key="d2">The oral surface of the Thick Fleshy Starfish is smooth and pale yellow in colour, with tube feet.&lt;SEP&gt;The oral surface of P. echinaster is pale in colour.&lt;SEP&gt;Smooth oral surface of the Inflexible Rigid Star.&lt;SEP&gt;Smooth oral surface.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b7d87a9fdd6796fbc3a24c40022179ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-01224e247c54c26376338d1d355035dc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-43c53974450202fe6a82416f946fc26f</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097489</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Chondraster Elattosis">
  <data key="d0">Chondraster Elattosis</data>
  <data key="d1">species</data>
  <data key="d2">Chondraster Elattosis is a species of starfish that does not inflate and is leathery. It is a South African endemic found on the West and South Coasts of South Africa at depths from 400 to 1000+ meters.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-21ece0344bd87c400d1d234a341d632a</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781095618</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Spoladaster Brachyactis">
  <data key="d0">Spoladaster Brachyactis</data>
  <data key="d1">species</data>
  <data key="d2">Spoladaster Brachyactis is a species of starfish that is pentagonal, cushion-like, often inflated, with papillae on the aboral surface and a smooth ventral side. It is found on the West and South Coasts of South Africa at depths from 40 to 205+ meters, up to 160 mm diameter, with speckled brilliant orange aboral surface and pale cream oral surface.&lt;SEP&gt;Spoladaster brachyactis is a starfish species that inflates and is not as leathery compared with Spoladaster veneris.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-21ece0344bd87c400d1d234a341d632a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1ff0eb99ae21e17d67fdd1dbba08d515</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097510</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Spoladaster Veneris">
  <data key="d0">Spoladaster Veneris</data>
  <data key="d1">species</data>
  <data key="d2">Spoladaster Veneris is a similar species to Chondraster Elattosis; it inflates and is less leathery compared to Chondraster Elattosis.&lt;SEP&gt;Spoladaster veneris is a starfish species with code name SpoBra, belonging to Phylum Echinodermata, Class Asteroidea, Order Valvatida, Family Poraniidae, Genus Spoladaster, and Species veneris. Its common name is Inflated Star.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-21ece0344bd87c400d1d234a341d632a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1ff0eb99ae21e17d67fdd1dbba08d515</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097509</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Phylum Echinodermata">
  <data key="d0">Phylum Echinodermata</data>
  <data key="d1">taxon</data>
  <data key="d2">Phylum Echinodermata is the taxonomic phylum to which the starfish species Chondraster Elattosis and Spoladaster Brachyactis belong.&lt;SEP&gt;A taxonomic phylum of marine invertebrates characterized by radial symmetry and a water vascular system, presented on page 430 of the document.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-21ece0344bd87c400d1d234a341d632a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2cad148e1c5a94e8c3f62bdfee2b66fa</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097504</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Cushion-Like Body">
  <data key="d0">Cushion-Like Body</data>
  <data key="d1">anatomical_feature</data>
  <data key="d2">The cushion-like body is a pentagonal, inflated shape characteristic of Spoladaster Brachyactis when landed.&lt;SEP&gt;The organism has a cushion-like body that appears inflated when landed.&lt;SEP&gt;The body is cushion-like and often inflated when landed, slowly deflating out of water.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-21ece0344bd87c400d1d234a341d632a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6312bf3bcdf9b3397dffc439b6ad9d04&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-193d40aeb45ee8e91a4034e163403a2b</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097500</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Papillae on Aboral Surface">
  <data key="d0">Papillae on Aboral Surface</data>
