  <data key="d5">1781095627</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Thick Fleshy Starfish">
  <data key="d0">Thick Fleshy Starfish</data>
  <data key="d1">species</data>
  <data key="d2">An unidentified starfish species described on page 430 with inflexible rigid star, thick solid spongy disc, pentagonal shape, indistinct marginal plates, distinct madreporite, fine raised bumps (sheaths of adambulacral spines) forming rows along arms, no spines, double rows of tube feet, no marginal plates visible, distinct patterning on aboral surface when brooding. Colour bright pink to orange on aboral, pale yellow on oral. Size up to 230 mm diameter. Distribution: South African endemic, West and South Coasts of South Africa.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781095627</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Central Disc">
  <data key="d0">Central Disc</data>
  <data key="d1">anatomical_feature</data>
  <data key="d2">The central disc of Luidia africana is the region from which arms extend, and arms break off easily from it.&lt;SEP&gt;The central body part of the starfish from which the arms break off easily.&lt;SEP&gt;Central disc from which arms break off easily.&lt;SEP&gt;The central disc is the central body part from which arms break off easily.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0f7451703f2287af83a619489c9a745&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2d7a926bdefa616f9a22865cd82d942c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f415192a0ac774637b252cf14199cb4e</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097485</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Arms">
  <data key="d0">Arms</data>
  <data key="d1">anatomical_feature</data>
  <data key="d2">Arms of Luidia africana are long, flexible, flattened, tapering, strap-like, usually five in number, and break off easily from the central disc.&lt;SEP&gt;Long, flexible, flattened, tapering, strap-like arms that usually break off from central disc easily. Usually five arms.&lt;SEP&gt;The arms are long, flexible, flattened, tapering, strap-like, usually five in number, and break off easily from the central disc.&lt;SEP&gt;The starfish has arms with rows of adambulacral spine sheaths.&lt;SEP&gt;Fairly rigid arms with ends often turning upwards or curling inwards, with strong spines along the base.&lt;SEP&gt;Arms are appendages of the species; for P. echinaster they are clearly defined, while for Diplopteraster multipes they are less clearly defined and the species is more cushion-like.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-01224e247c54c26376338d1d355035dc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2d7a926bdefa616f9a22865cd82d942c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-272e62d6d62e10360c47dab598eb09e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-37cbd16434444d9480d8632be65be39c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f415192a0ac774637b252cf14199cb4e</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097490</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Aboral Margin Edge">
  <data key="d0">Aboral Margin Edge</data>
  <data key="d1">anatomical_feature</data>
  <data key="d2">The aboral margin edge of Luidia africana has distinct spines protruding from it.&lt;SEP&gt;Edge of the aboral margin where distinct spines protrude.&lt;SEP&gt;The edge on the aboral side of the invertebrate where distinct spines protrude.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2d7a926bdefa616f9a22865cd82d942c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f415192a0ac774637b252cf14199cb4e</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097496</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Spines">
  <data key="d0">Spines</data>
  <data key="d1">anatomical_feature</data>
  <data key="d2">Spines are present on the aboral margin edge of Luidia africana.&lt;SEP&gt;Distinct spines protruding from the aboral margin edge.&lt;SEP&gt;Distinct spines that protrude from the aboral margin edge.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2d7a926bdefa616f9a22865cd82d942c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f415192a0ac774637b252cf14199cb4e</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097496</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Adambulacral Spines Sheaths">
  <data key="d0">Adambulacral Spines Sheaths</data>
  <data key="d1">anatomical_feature</data>
  <data key="d2">Fine raised bumps (sheaths of adambulacral spines) form distinct rows along each arm in the Thick Fleshy Starfish.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
