  <data key="d0">Clark Am And Downey Me 1992</data>
  <data key="d1">document</data>
  <data key="d2">A reference document: Clark AM and Downey ME. 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic (Volume 3). Chapman and Hall: London. p. 20.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781095632</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Marginal Plates">
  <data key="d0">Marginal Plates</data>
  <data key="d1">anatomical_feature</data>
  <data key="d2">Marginal plates are indistinct or not visible in the Thick Fleshy Starfish, present along the arms but not apparent.&lt;SEP&gt;Indistinct marginal plates on the Inflexible Rigid Star, not visible on the aboral or oral surface.&lt;SEP&gt;Indistinct marginal plates, not visible.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-01224e247c54c26376338d1d355035dc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-43c53974450202fe6a82416f946fc26f</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097487</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Spongy Disc">
  <data key="d0">Spongy Disc</data>
  <data key="d1">anatomical_feature</data>
  <data key="d2">The spongy disc is the thick, solid, spongy central part of the Thick Fleshy Starfish, pentagonal in shape.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781095633</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Aboral Surface">
  <data key="d0">Aboral Surface</data>
  <data key="d1">anatomical_feature</data>
  <data key="d2">The aboral surface of the Thick Fleshy Starfish is smooth, bright pink to orange in colour, and can have distinct patterning when brooding.&lt;SEP&gt;Smooth aboral surface of the Inflexible Rigid Star, with distinct patterning when brooding.&lt;SEP&gt;Smooth aboral surface with distinct patterning when brooding.&lt;SEP&gt;The upper surface of the organism, covered with papillae.&lt;SEP&gt;The aboral surface is covered with papillae.&lt;SEP&gt;The aboral surface is the upper surface of a starfish-like organism, mentioned in the description of Lophaster quadrispinus as having many dense raised tubercles.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-01224e247c54c26376338d1d355035dc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6312bf3bcdf9b3397dffc439b6ad9d04&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-272e62d6d62e10360c47dab598eb09e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-43c53974450202fe6a82416f946fc26f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-193d40aeb45ee8e91a4034e163403a2b</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097489</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Port Elizabeth">
  <data key="d0">Port Elizabeth</data>
  <data key="d1">other</data>
  <data key="d2">Port Elizabeth is a city on the South Coast of South Africa, within the distribution range of Luidia africana.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781095634</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="West Coast Of South Africa">
  <data key="d0">West Coast Of South Africa</data>
  <data key="d1">distribution</data>
  <data key="d2">The West Coast of South Africa is a coastal region along the Atlantic Ocean, part of the distribution range for both Luidia africana and the Thick Fleshy Starfish.&lt;SEP&gt;The West Coast of South Africa is a distribution area for Poraniopsis echinaster.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-83d371544d6eb48b5321717428ea68f1</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781097495</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="South Coast Of South Africa">
  <data key="d0">South Coast Of South Africa</data>
  <data key="d1">other</data>
  <data key="d2">The South Coast of South Africa is a coastal region along the Indian Ocean, part of the distribution range for both Luidia africana and the Thick Fleshy Starfish.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1781095634</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="South Africa">
  <data key="d0">South Africa</data>
  <data key="d1">other</data>
  <data key="d2">South Africa is the country where the described starfish species are endemic to its coasts.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c93021c72fb2fa03f2a5d62bc0adb874</data>
  <data key="d4">Field-Guide-to-SA-Offshore-Marine-Invertebrates_web-full-version_compressed.pdf</data>
